Java application usually go through two stages : 
1. Build stage -> compile the code and create a jar/war file
2. Runtime stage -> run the JAR using the Java runtime


  This is why Java dockerfiles are almost always use multi stage builds

  Typical java project structure 

  project
 ├── pom.xml
 ├── src/
 │   └── main/java/...
 └── target/
      └── app.jar   (generated after build)

  The target/app.jar files is the built application 

  
2.Dockerfile for Java (Maven + Spring Boot )

FROM maven:3.9-eclipse-temurin-21 AS build   # Pull the image which contains Java,maven,build tools
WORKDIR /app                                 
COPY pom.xml .                           # Copy the dependency file       
RUN mvn dependency:go-offline            # This download's all the dependencies
COPY src ./src                           # Copy the source code 
RUN mvn package -DskipTests              # Build the application 


FROM eclipse-temurin:21-jre              # This image contians only the java runtime 
WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=build /app/target/*.jar app.jar  # This copies the JAR file created in the build stage
EXPOSE 8080
CMD ["java","-jar","app.jar"]                  # This start the java application 
  
